{"title_page": "Lloyds Bank coprolite", "text_new": "{{short description|Fossilized piece of human dung from Viking-era York in the Unted Kingdom.}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{Infobox Artifact\n| name          = Lloyds Bank coprolite\n| image         =[[File:Lloydsbankcoprolite 001.jpg|250px]]\n| image_caption = Lloyds Bank Coprolite at [[Jorvik Viking Centre]]\n| material      =  Human excrement<ref name=\"WSJ\"/>\n| created       = 9th century AD\n| discovered    = 1972, Coppergate, York\n| location      = [[Jorvik Viking Centre]] \n}}\nThe '''Lloyds Bank coprolite''' is a large [[paleofaeces]], or desiccated human dung specimen, recovered by [[archaeologists]] from [[York Archaeological Trust]] excavating the [[Viking]] settlement of [[J\u00f3rv\u00edk]] (now [[York]]) in [[England]].\n\n==Description==\nThe coprolite was found in 1972 beneath the site of what was to become the York branch of [[Lloyds Bank (historic)|Lloyds Bank]] and may be the largest example of [[fossil]]ised human [[faeces]] ever found, measuring {{convert|20|cm|in|0}} long and {{convert|5|cm|in|0}} wide. Analysis of the stool has indicated that its producer subsisted largely on [[meat]] and [[bread]] whilst the presence of several hundred [[parasite|parasitic]] eggs suggests they were riddled with [[Intestinal parasite|intestinal worm]]s. In 1991, York Archaeological Trust employee and [[Scatology|paleoscatologist]], Dr Andrew Jones, made international news with his appraisal of the item for insurance purposes: \"This is the most exciting piece of excrement I've ever seen... In its own way, it's as irreplaceable as the Crown Jewels\".<ref name=\"WSJ\">{{cite news|last1=Horwitz|first1=Tony|title=Endangered Feces: Paleo-Scatologist Plumbs Old Privies --- It May Not Be the Lost Ark, But Then, Andrew Isn't Exactly Indiana Jones|work=Wall Street Journal|date=9 September 1991|page=A1}}</ref>\n\n==Display==\nThe specimen was put on display at the city's [[DIG: an archaeological adventure|Archaeological Resource Centre]] (now known as DIG), the outreach and education institution run by the [[York Archaeological Trust]].<ref name=\"guardian\">{{cite news |title=Museum's broken treasure not just any old shit |author=Simon Jeffery |url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2003/jun/06/artsandhumanities.arts1 |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |date=6 June 2003 |accessdate=5 February 2013}}</ref> In 2003, it broke into three pieces after being dropped whilst on exhibition to a party of visitors. {{As of|2003}}, efforts were underway to reconstruct it.<ref name=\"guardian\"/> It has been displayed at [[Jorvik Viking Centre]] since 2008.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://vimeo.com/18311924 Bone: The Man Behind the Lloyds Bank Turd] - Video discussing the discovery and analysis of the coprolite\n\n{{Commons category|Lloyds Bank coprolite}}\n\n[[Category:Anglo-Norse England]]\n[[Category:Collections of the York Archaeological Trust]]\n[[Category:Feces]]\n[[Category:History of North Yorkshire]]\n[[Category:Archaeology of England]]\n[[Category:Lloyds Banking Group]]\n\n\n{{UK-archaeology-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Fossilized piece of human dung from Viking-era York in the Unted Kingdom.}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{Infobox Artifact\n| name          = Lloyds Bank coprolite\n| image         =[[File:Lloydsbankcoprolite 001.jpg|250px]]\n| image_caption = Lloyds Bank Coprolite at [[Jorvik Viking Centre]]\n| material      =  Human excrement<ref name=\"WSJ\"/>\n| created       = 9th century AD\n| discovered    = 1972, Coppergate, York\n| location      = [[Jorvik Viking Centre]] \n}}\nThe '''Lloyds Bank coprolite''' is a large [[paleofaeces]], or desiccated human dung specimen, recovered by [[archaeologists]] from [[York Archaeological Trust]] excavating the [[Viking]] settlement of [[J\u00f3rv\u00edk]] (now [[York]]) in [[England]].\n\n==Description==\nThe coprolite was found in 1972 beneath the site of what was to become the York branch of [[Lloyds Bank (historic)|Lloyds Bank]] and may be the largest example of [[fossil]]ised human [[faeces]] ever found, measuring {{convert|20|cm|in|0}} long and {{convert|5|cm|in|0}} wide. Analysis of the stool has indicated that its producer subsisted largely on [[meat]] and [[bread]] whilst the presence of several hundred [[parasite|parasitic]] eggs suggests they were riddled with [[Intestinal parasite|intestinal worm]]s. In 1991, York Archaeological Trust employee and [[Scatology|paleoscatologist]], Dr Andrew Jones, made international news with his appraisal of the item for insurance purposes: \"This is the most exciting piece of excrement I've ever seen... In its own way, it's as irreplaceable as the Crown Jewels\".<ref name=\"WSJ\">{{cite news|last1=Horwitz|first1=Tony|title=Endangered Feces: Paleo-Scatologist Plumbs Old Privies --- It May Not Be the Lost Ark, But Then, Andrew Isn't Exactly Indiana Jones|work=Wall Street Journal|date=9 September 1991|page=A1}}</ref>\n\n==Display==\nThe specimen was put on display at the city's [[DIG: an archaeological adventure|Archaeological Resource Centre]] (now known as DIG), the outreach and education institution run by the [[York Archaeological Trust]].<ref name=\"guardian\">{{cite news |title=Museum's broken treasure not just any old shit |author=Simon Jeffery |url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2003/jun/06/artsandhumanities.arts1 |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |date=6 June 2003 |accessdate=5 February 2013}}</ref> In 2003, it broke into three pieces after being dropped whilst on exhibition to a party of visitors. {{As of|2003}}, efforts were underway to reconstruct it.<ref name=\"guardian\"/> It has been displayed at [[Jorvik Viking Centre]] since 2008.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://vimeo.com/18311924 Bone: The Man Behind the Lloyds Bank Turd] - Video discussing the discovery and analysis of the coprolite\n\n{{Commons category|Lloyds Bank coprolite}}\n\n[[Category:Anglo-Norse England]]\n[[Category:Collections of the York Archaeological Trust]]\n[[Category:Feces]]\n[[Category:History of North Yorkshire]]\n[[Category:Archaeology of England]]\n\n\n{{UK-archaeology-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Error", "label": "safe", "comment": "addedCategory:Lloyds Banking GroupusingHotCat", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lloyds_Bank_coprolite"}
{"title_page": "Candler Almshouses", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=January 2016}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2016}}\n{{Infobox Historic Site\n| name =Candler Almshouses\n| native_name =\n| image = \n| caption =\n| locmapin = \n| map_caption =\n| location = Twickenham,  [[London Borough of Richmond upon Thames]],  England\n| area =\n| built = 1936 (current buildings)\n| built_for = \n| demolished =\n| rebuilt = \n| restored =\n| restored_by =\n| architect = \n| architecture =\n| governing_body =\n| designation1 = \n| designation1_offname =\n| designation1_date =\n| designation1_number =\n| designation2 =\n| designation2_offname =\n| designation2_date =\n| designation2_number =\n| designation3 =\n| designation3_offname =\n| designation3_date =\n| designation3_number =\n| designation4 =\n| designation4_offname =\n| designation4_date =\n| designation4_number =\n| designation5 =\n| designation5_offname =\n| designation5_date =\n| designation5_number =\n}}\n\n'''Candler Almshouses''' are  [[almshouses]] at 79 Amyand Park Road, [[Twickenham]], TW1 3HJ in the [[London Borough of Richmond upon Thames]], England.\n\nThe ten almshouses are now managed by The [[Richmond Charities]].<ref name=\"Charities\">{{cite web | url=http://www.richmondcharities.org.uk/almshouses/candler-almshouses| title=Candler Almshouses | publisher=The [[Richmond Charities]] | accessdate=31 July 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"Charity\">{{cite web | url=http://www.charityperformance.com/charity-details.php?id=12315 | title=Richmond Charities | publisher=DG Publishing | work=Charity Performance | accessdate=31 July 2015 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140415095906/http://www.charityperformance.com/charity-details.php?id=12315 | archivedate=15 April 2014 | df=dmy-all }}</ref> New residents are accepted from 65 years of age.<ref name=\"EAC\">{{cite web | url=http://www.housingcare.org/housing-care/facility-info-158759-candler-amshouses-twickenham-england.aspx| title=Candler Almshouses | publisher=Elderly Accommodation Counsel (EAC) | accessdate=31 July 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe current almshouses were built in 1936. They are named after William Candler (1826\u20131907), a [[grocer]] in [[Twickenham]] who left money to build them.<ref name=\"Charities\"/><ref name=\"Victoria\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.british-history.ac.uk/vch/middx/vol3/p166 |title=A History of the County of Middlesex: Volume 3, Shepperton, Staines, Stanwell, Sunbury, Teddington, Heston and Isleworth, Twickenham, Cowley, Cranford, West Drayton, Greenford, Hanwell, Harefield and Harlington, p.166. Originally published by Victoria County History, London, 1962.|author= [[Susan Reynolds|Reynolds, Susan]] (ed.)|date = 1962| website= [[British History Online]] |access-date=20 November 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Alexander\">{{Cite journal |title= William Candler and the Almshouses|last=Alexander |first=Peter H |date=June 2003 |journal=West Middlesex Family History Journal |url= http://www.west-middlesex-fhs.org.uk/downloads/2003%20No%202%20June.pdfvolume=21 |issue=2 |pages=26-29 |issn=0142-517X}}</ref> He is buried in [[Richmond Cemetery]].<ref name=\"Historical A-L\">{{cite web | url=http://www.richmond.gov.uk/home/leisure_and_culture/local_history_and_heritage/people_of_historical_note_buried_in_the_borough_a_to_l.htm | title=People of historical note buried in the borough A to L | publisher=[[London Borough of Richmond upon Thames]] | accessdate=24 January 2016 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151222094512/http://www.richmond.gov.uk/home/leisure_and_culture/local_history_and_heritage/people_of_historical_note_buried_in_the_borough_a_to_l.htm# | archive-date=22 December 2015 | url-status=dead | df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of almshouses in the United Kingdom]]\n\n==Notes and references==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.richmondcharities.org.uk/ [[Richmond Charities|The Richmond Charities]]]\n\n{{Almshouses in Richmond upon Thames}}\n{{LB Richmond}}\n[[Category:1936 establishments in England]]\n\n[[Category:Almshouses in London]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures completed in 1936]]\n[[Category:History of the London Borough of Richmond upon Thames]]\n[[Category:Twickenham]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=January 2016}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2016}}\n{{Infobox Historic Site\n| name =Candler Almshouses\n| native_name =\n| image = \n| caption =\n| locmapin = \n| map_caption =\n| location = Twickenham,  [[London Borough of Richmond upon Thames]],  England\n| area =\n| built = 1936 (current buildings)\n| built_for = \n| demolished =\n| rebuilt = \n| restored =\n| restored_by =\n| architect = \n| architecture =\n| governing_body =\n| designation1 = \n| designation1_offname =\n| designation1_date =\n| designation1_number =\n| designation2 =\n| designation2_offname =\n| designation2_date =\n| designation2_number =\n| designation3 =\n| designation3_offname =\n| designation3_date =\n| designation3_number =\n| designation4 =\n| designation4_offname =\n| designation4_date =\n| designation4_number =\n| designation5 =\n| designation5_offname =\n| designation5_date =\n| designation5_number =\n}}\n\n'''Candler Almshouses''' are  [[almshouses]] at 79 Amyand Park Road, [[Twickenham]], TW1 3HJ in the [[London Borough of Richmond upon Thames]], England.\n\nThe ten almshouses are now managed by The [[Richmond Charities]].<ref name=\"Charities\">{{cite web | url=http://www.richmondcharities.org.uk/almshouses/candler-almshouses| title=Candler Almshouses | publisher=The [[Richmond Charities]] | accessdate=31 July 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"Charity\">{{cite web | url=http://www.charityperformance.com/charity-details.php?id=12315 | title=Richmond Charities | publisher=DG Publishing | work=Charity Performance | accessdate=31 July 2015 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140415095906/http://www.charityperformance.com/charity-details.php?id=12315 | archivedate=15 April 2014 | df=dmy-all }}</ref> New res